                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/2456: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-10T14:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 10, 1919, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your October 3, 7 p.m.</p>
                <p>The Department perceives no objection to the proposal of the banks to let the
                    option for the Currency loan lapse unless it be on the grounds pointed out in
                    the latter part of your telegram in view whereof it is desired that you
                    reemphasize this Government’s former reservation contained in the Legation’s
                    note No. 857 to the Foreign Office of October 8, 1918,<note n="19"
                        xml:id="d483fn19">
                        <ref target="frus1918#pg_159">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1918, p. 159</ref>.</note> as
                    to its right to be consulted in any project of currency reform which the Chinese
                    Government may propose to adopt.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
